SIMPLE: pavilion
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pavilion
<hw>Pa*vil"ion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>pavillon</ets>, fr. L. <ets>pavilio</ets> a butterfly, also, a
tent, because spread out like a butterfly's wings.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A temporary movable habitation; a large tent; a marquee; esp., a
tent raised on posts.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧[The] Greeks do pitch their brave
<xex>pavilions</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A single body or mass of
building, contained within simple walls and a single roof, whether
insulated, as in the park or garden of a larger edifice, or united with
other parts, and forming an angle or central feature of a large
pile.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A flag, colors, ensign, or
banner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Tent</er>
<fld>(Her.)</fld></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>That part of a brilliant which lies between the
girdle and collet. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Brilliant</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The auricle of the ear; also, the
fimbriated extremity of the Fallopian tube.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A covering; a canopy; figuratively, the
sky.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>pavilion</qex> of heaven is bare.</q>
<rj><qau>Shelley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pavilion</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pavilion
<hw>Pa*vil"ion</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Pavilioned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pavilioning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To furnish or cover with, or
shelter in, a tent or tents.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The field <qex>pavilioned</qex> with his guardians bright.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pavin</ent>⟦br⟧
